[Student "S"]
{In response to partner's Stayman bid you bid 2\D to indicate no 4-card Major. Partner now bids 2\H.  

In response to partner's Stayman bid you bid 2\D to indicate no 4-card Major. Partner now bids 2\H. 

Partner's bid shows 5\Hs, and by inference, 4 \Ss. You hand does not provide an 8-card fit in either Major, so with 17 points you say 3NT.

North plays 3NT. East leads the \DQ.

Winner List: \S = 0 : \H = 2 : \D = 2 : \C = 4 :: Total = 8

You need one more winner and without question it must come from the \H suit. 

Your problem is finding dummy entries, all dummy has is the \H A K. 

You must find the \Hs split 3-3. You must also duck a \H to keep a valuable entry. Win the \D and play the \H7, ducking in dummy. 

West will win the \H and return a \D which you win in your hand. You now play your last \H  to dummy, and if the suit was originally 3-3 you will win 4 \H  tricks.

The "brute force" method for establishing dummy's \H suit would be to play \H A K, then another. If they split 3-3 your last two \Hs would be winners.

Of course you'd look pretty stupid to have those 2 \H winners in dummy and no way to reach them.

So you use the duck instead.}
[Play "W"]DQ

