[Student "S"]
{With 9 points you are in the game-invitational range. And with a 4-card \H suit you should use Stayman. You bid 2\C and partner says 2\D. What is your next bid? 

With 9 points you are in the game-invitational range. And with a 4-card \H suit you should use Stayman. You bid 2\C and partner says 2\D. What is your next bid?

You are still in game-invitational range, but now you invite partner with 2NT. He replies 3NT and that ends the bidding.

The contract would be 3NT played by West.

East plays 3NT. South leads the \ST. You cross your fingers and put on dummy's \SJ. No good, North covers with the \SQ and you are forced to take your \SK at the first trick.

Winner List: \S = 1 : \H = 3 : \D = 1 : \C = 1 :: Total = 6

Not only do you need 3 more winners, you need to get them without losing the lead because the instant you lose the lead South will take all his \S winners. You can <b>HOPE</b> that will only be 3 of them but you can't depend on it.

The \C suit is your only hope. If North holds the \CK you can finesse him out of it. However, if he has \C K x x and refuses to cover your \CJ, you will have to have a second entry to dummy to cash the good \Cs. 

As it happens, you do have two entries, the \HA and \HQ! You just have to sacrifice your \HK to use them both. At trick 2 play your small \H to the \HQ. Play the \CJ, letting it ride when North plays low. Play a small \C to your \CQ. Play the \CA, dropping North's \CK. And finally, play your \HK to dummy's \HA so you can enjoy cashing those two good \Cs.

Bridge is a nice game.

You sacrifice one sure \H winner to create a second dummy entry which creates two \C winners.}
[Play "W"]ST

